@lucian [τ, נ] SN41 Can we discuss that the current challenge setup is unfair to miners because of non-constant testing input?
For instance not every /12/ is equal, but it doesn't appear that every miner gets a copy of that /12/ from the validator
they each get their own unique which is obvious to avoid caching, but unfair in terms of difficulty
some miners may be served a harder one, while others an easier one, and the difference can be drastic. a 5 second /12/ vs a 30 second timeout
this leads to spikes in a miners incentive that increases churn on the subnet and makes mining less stable regardless of machine capabilities

the people being deregistered, if we look at stats, are not the worst performing miners. Often their consensus places them even in the higher echelons of miners, and given one single update interval, will be back to normal incentive, still above the actual worst performing miners, it's my belief that the cause of this is the following:

1. uneven concurrent requests
2. uneven challenge difficulty

a miner shouldn't have to deal with unequal testing across miners. Each miner should be evaluated equally. I have no idea how to fix the uneven challenge difficulty with a hashcat based test, as it's often difficult to evaluate the complexity of the challenge without actually evaluating said challenge

if we look at a healthy subnet, the deregisters are ones that have been bottom incentive for hours upon hours, machines that have died, etc. On our subnet its people with 450 incentive getting wrecked by a 4x concurrent or multiple harder difficulty /12/s etc. Just like on other subnets that have this "unequal" testing method you can observe V shaped patterns in weights being set for each miner. Miner gets a 4x -> gets tanked by whatever validator gets the short end of the stick (the longest request) -> still has amazing consensus -> gets restored by the other validators next weight set, but that period where they get tanked deregisters them / increases churn, meanwhile you can have a guy that's been at 410 incentive for 24 hours but has been lucky enough to not get concurrents. That person deserves the deregister, and indeed on most subnets, this is the case. The lowest average incentive miner is the deregistered one. This problem is even further magnified (perhaps the primary culprit) by weight copiers. You get that 4x -> tank one validator -> 3 other validators copy weights

Because the hashcat challenge serves no purpose other than the evaluate the performance of a miners machine, it's nothing that the validator would need to forward an API request for, etc, and concurrency is **NOT** the focus, the task for completing a challenge should be initiated by the _miner_ not the validator. The allocation should still be initiated by the validator of course, and a miner should publish their axon for this purpose. The validator will keep a 1 hour bucket of challenges for each miner (with a cap or unlimited but they need to complete x per hour) They may complete these as fast as they want within that 1 hour by pulling a task from the validator, and your score will be quite similar to how it is now, essentially **nothing **would change there. I see no real downsides to something like this (not to say this is the right idea, but perhaps something similar) as it leads to the same result we have right now in terms of how your miner will rank, but with greater stability for all. no one receives an unequal advantage from this change, every miner instead gains stability. It still leaves the unequal challenge issue, but entirely eliminates the unequal concurrency problem which is likely higher impact. if you're a top miner right now, you will continue being a top miner, and will even have greater stability because you're kicking butt and are on a equal playing field.

And inb4 "just deal with concurrents" from someone here (not u lucian) - cool make that the goal of the subnet then and apply it to ALL miners equally, that's entirely valid if its equal, theres other RPS/concurrency testing subnets out there, but I see no actual practical purpose for this that is in line with the subnet vision in any way

Very interesting ideas—thank you! A few notes:

- Unless a miner has a validator blacklisted, all miners will receive challenges at the same time (relatively, within a few seconds). The “uneven concurrent requests” point you mentioned doesn’t really occur, though it technically does within a few-second range as validators loop through all the miners to send them challenges

- I 100% agree with some challenges of the same difficulty taking more/less time to solve, even when they’re generated from the same validator at the same time. One issue with sending the exact same challenge to everyone is the ability for miners to calculate the answer on one very powerful machine and then just submit it on other machines, not needing to have any real compute power (though hashcat isn’t a great measure of compute power. Its a measure of hashing power)

- As for having a “bucket” of challenges assigned to each miner that they need to solve, it would suffer from the same issue of challenges of the same difficulty not necessarily being equal, though it would alleviate some of the concurrency problems. If, however, the mechanism incorporated the same challenges for all miners to allow it to be fair, we’d run into the issue of miners using one powerful machine and submitting the answer(s) across other machines

- The biggest issue is needing hashcat at all, which is why other scoring mechanisms are being explored at the moment. Hashcat is temporary and has likely lasted longer than anyone wanted, but it’s been a necessary evil up until this point. One downside to adjusting the current mechanism means having less hands on testing/developing the new one

@jondurbin This is a fair point, but the miner should not optimize this subnet by doing what I did and what I’m sure others are doing. Most of the actual issues are outside a miners control. A large amount of the validators are cheaters. They do not contribute to the ecosystem, they copy weights, and they cause the entire ecosystem to lose trust.

The problem is further exacerbated by subnets like this one which have what I’d consider to be big flaws in their testing method. Because the test, despite its purpose being to evaluate the performance of one’s machine, isn’t equal, miners have an increased chance at performing badly for a single validator. This would normally be sorta fine on a subnet with honest validators, but ours are not. Instead, the miner is dropped in incentive unfairly due to 4-5 validators that tag along to that weight set because they are copiers. This churns miners, and lowers miner trust in the subnet (which isn’t high already).

The scoring mechanism itself should be changed, yes, but it’s not exactly the problem with concurrents.

If we look at the subnet goal, it’s to be a marketplace for machines. Right away, there are things like IP restrictions to ensure miners are submitting one unique machine. Miners have their machine evaluated with hashcat which has its flaws as described above, but does serve as a basic benchmark. The answer to this isn’t to send your tasks off to a group of machines, that defeats the purpose of evaluating your single machine, yet that’s what is essentially required.

@Andrew O [τ, τ] what you said regarding that it should be equal, I’m not sure how you determine this.

Validators are not synced to each other, they will be sending tasks at different times. This means there is always the possibility of two validators querying the same miner. Furthermore, due to the UID selection, and the batching of requests, there is absolutely zero guarantee that every miner would encounter this set of concurrents. I don’t see in any way how we can say this is equal. Is it equal sometimes? Sure. Can you prove it’s always equal? No.

Simple design pattern changes can easily solve this problem. Other subnets already do this. I also think for any subnet to survive in the real world, their testing mechanism should be provably equal. You can’t trust a bittensor product when the miners aren’t actually being evaluated how they say they are, and these unfair evaluations just lead to shortcuts like mine which further erode trust that any outsider could have in this ecosystem.
